  "grammarPoint": {
    "title": "Frequency words, and Russian's double negative",
    "explanation": "Frequency words go right before the verb: **всегда́** (always) → **ре́дко** (rarely) → **никогда́** (never). \n\nRussian *requires* **не** together with a negative word — this isn't a mistake, it's the rule: **Я никогда́ не ем мя́со** literally \"I never not eat meat\" = I never eat meat. Drop the **не** and the sentence is wrong.",
    "examples": [
      { "ru": "Я всегда́ пью ко́фе у́тром.", "en": "I always drink coffee in the morning." },
      { "ru": "Ты ча́сто чита́ешь?", "en": "Do you read often?" },
      { "ru": "Я иногда́ смотрю́ телеви́зор.", "en": "I sometimes watch television." },
      { "ru": "Я никогда́ не ем мя́со.", "en": "I never eat meat.", "note": "никогда + не, both required" }
    ]
  },

  "vocab": [
